    "\n",
    "### 1. Vote-to-Seat Conversion Advantage (AITC)\n",
    "AITC's 10.2% vote lead over BJP translated into a **47% seat advantage** — showing how first-past-the-post systems amplify majorities. AITC's vote distribution was more geographically efficient.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2. SC Seats Were the True Battleground\n",
    "In General seats, AITC dominated (167 vs 33). But in **SC reserved seats**, BJP almost matched AITC (35 vs 38). SC constituencies will be critical in 2026.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3. 68 Swing Seats Could Decide 2026\n",
    "With 68 direct BJP-AITC seats having margins under 10,000 votes, and BJP holding 31 of them — a small swing of votes in these seats can completely flip the assembly.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4. Urban Voter Apathy\n",
    "Kolkata urban constituencies had turnout as low as 50% (Jorasanko), compared to 90%+ in rural seats. **Urban voter mobilization is a key unopened opportunity** for both parties in 2026.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 5. Generational Gap in Leadership\n",
    "BJP elected MLAs averaged **48.2 years** vs AITC's **56.9 years** — an 8.7-year generational difference. BJP's younger leadership could be a growing factor in future elections.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 6. Left Front Collapse\n",
    "CPI(M) + INC combined won 7.8% of votes but **zero seats** — a dramatic collapse from their 2011 majority. Vote splitting between Left and Congress hurt both parties severely.\n",
